    <h2>The Space Between Inline-Block Elements</h2>
    <p>One important distinction with inline-block elements is that they are not always touching, or displayed directly against one another. Usually a small space will exist between two inline-block elements. This space is normal and can be controlled.</p>

    <h2>What Is the Box Model?</h2>
    <p>According to the box model concept, every element on a page is a rectangular box and may have width, height, padding, borders, and margins.</p>

    <p><strong>Every element on a page is a rectangular box.</strong></p>

    <img src="https://learn.shayhowe.com/assets/images/courses/html-css/opening-the-box-model/box-model.png" alt="Box Model" style="max-width:100%;margin:20px 0;">

    <h2>Working with the Box Model</h2>
    <p>Every element is a rectangular box, with core properties: <code>width</code> and <code>height</code>. Padding, border, and margin expand the dimensions outward.</p>

    <pre><code>div {
  border: 6px solid #949599;
  height: 100px;
  margin: 20px;
  padding: 20px;
  width: 400px;
}</code></pre>

    <p>Total width formula:</p>
    <pre><code>total-width = margin-right + border-right + padding-right + width + padding-left + border-left + margin-left</code></pre>

    <p>Total height formula:</p>
    <pre><code>total-height = margin-top + border-top + padding-top + height + padding-bottom + border-bottom + margin-bottom</code></pre>

    <img src="https://learn.shayhowe.com/assets/images/courses/html-css/opening-the-box-model/box-model.png" alt="Box Model Breakdown" style="max-width:100%;margin:20px 0;">

    <p>Example calculations:</p>
    <pre><code>Width: 492px = 20px + 6px + 20px + 400px + 20px + 6px + 20px
Height: 192px = 20px + 6px + 20px + 100px + 20px + 6px + 20px</code></pre>

    <h2>Width & Height</h2>

    <p>Block-level elements default to 100% width, inline elements expand to content. Inline-level elements do not accept width or height.</p>

    <pre><code>div {
  width: 400px;
  height: 100px;
}</code></pre>

    <h2>Margin & Padding</h2>

    <p>Margins create space outside an element. Padding creates space inside an element.</p>

    <pre><code>div {
  margin: 20px;
  padding: 20px;
}</code></pre>

    <h2>Borders</h2>

    <pre><code>div {
  border: 6px solid #949599;
}</code></pre>

    <p>Borders can have different styles and widths:</p>
    <pre><code>.border-solid   { border: 2px solid #9799a7; }
.border-double  { border: 6px double #9799a7; }
.border-dashed  { border: 8px dashed #9799a7; }
.border-dotted  { border: 4px dotted #9799a7; }</code></pre>

    <h2>Border Radius</h2>

    <pre><code>div {
  border-radius: 5px;
}</code></pre>

    <p>Border radius examples:</p>
    <pre><code>.border-rounded   { border-radius: 5px; }
.border-circle    { border-radius: 50%; }
.border-football  { border-radius: 15px 75px; }</code></pre>

    <h2>Box Sizing</h2>

    <p>CSS3 <code>box-sizing</code> changes how the box model calculates width and height.</p>

    <p>Content-box (default): width and height only for content, padding and border added outside.</p>

    <pre><code>div {
  -webkit-box-sizing: content-box;
  -moz-box-sizing: content-box;
  box-sizing: content-box;
}</code></pre>

    <p>Padding-box: width and height include padding but not border.</p>

    <pre><code>div {
  box-sizing: padding-box;
}</code></pre>

    <p>Border-box: width and height include padding and border.</p>

    <pre><code>div {
  box-sizing: border-box;
}</code></pre>

    <img src="https://www.washington.edu/accesscomputing/webd2/student/unit3/images/boxmodel.gif" alt="Box Sizing" style="max-width:100%;margin:20px 0;">

    <p>Generally, <code>border-box</code> is the easiest to work with because it simplifies calculations.</p>
